<h2 id="COMMUNITY">Community Connections</h2>
<h3>SCM and Release Management</h3>
<ul>
<li>Visit our <b><a
href="http://www.scmpatterns.com/wiki/"
 title="SCM Patterns Wiki">SCM Patterns Wiki</a></b>
and help to build a knowledge base about SCM
patterns and tools.</li>
<li><a href="http://acme.bradapp.net">Brad Appleton's Page</a>
has many links to SCM resources.</li>
<li> The <a
href="http://groups.yahoo.com/group/scm-patterns/">scm-patterns list
on Yahoo Groups</a> is a place to discuss the patterns in the book, as
well as other patterns. There is also a resources section. 
</li>

<li>A <a
href="http://www.nyetwork.org/wiki/SoftwareReleaseManagement">Software
Release Management</a> wiki maintained by Wim Kerkhoff.</li>

<li><a href="http://www.stickyminds.com">StickyMinds.com</a> has a
Configuration Management Zone. (Brad and Steve are Technical Advisors
for the CM Zone.)</li>

<li><a href="http://www.cmcrossroads.com" title="CM Crossroads">CM Crossroads</a> is an online community and resource center for Configuration Management
hosting interactive forums, a member contributed file cabinet and a
substantial resource links database.</li>
<li><a href="http://cmwiki.com/">Configuration Management wiki</a> at
CM Crossroads is a place to share information about the all aspects of
configuration management, not just SCM or SCM patterns.</li>

<li><a href="http://www.snuffybear.com/ucmcentral.htm" title="UCM
Central">UCM Central</a>, an Australian based,  non-commercial site dedicated to Configuration Management education.</li>
<li><a href="http://www.sdmagazine.com/">Software Development
Magazine</a> has regular articles on agile development and process.</li>
</ul>


<h3>Other Places of Interest</h3>
<ul>
<li>The <a href="http://www.agilealliance.org">Agile
Alliance</a>.</li>
<li>The <a href="http://c2.com/cgi/wiki">c2.com wiki</a> which
contains information about patterns, XP and other items of relevance
if you are interested in agile development.</li>
<li>The <a
href="http://groups.yahoo.com/group/extremeprogramming/">Extreme
Programming Group</a> at Yahoo Groups often discusses topic of
interest to those who want to develop code quickly and effectively.</li>
</ul>

